* ISPS Webinar: COVID-19 and Psychosis
:PROPERTIES:
:DATE: <2020-06-25 Thu>
:TITLE: ISPS webinar: COVID-19 and Psychosis
:TIME: 3 hours

** This was a three hour webinar composed of mental health care workers and people who have experienced psychosis.  Framed as a "trialogue" between the groups, a little like the NAMI framework

** Some things:
- People talked about a bunch of things (obviously) but some things were notable.
- One that came up repeatedly was how the lived experience of COVID-19 served as a "bridge" between the sick and the (well) health workers.  "Now you know what it feels like" said a patient to one of the doctors.  As if some feelings of paranoia and contagion, not trusting the government, etc that are often part of a psychotic syndrome, are now generally shared feelings.
- Dag Soderstrom - COVID has revealed whether we had established those "safe spaces" before the pandemic.
- For some with psychosis, if their spaces were safe, the Covid period was actually healthier for them.
- But for most, imaginably, isolation was destructive
- The technological gap became more obvious
- Rai Waddington - A global pandemic seems like just another one of my psychotic narratives - I've had alien conspiracies, I've had them all!  [Maybe it's easier for her to adjust]
- Some people with pre-existing anxiety have had less anxiety during the pandemic - things are more quiet, some better and deeper development of personal relationships

* Addiction Workshop, CP/AACP Psychiatry Update
:PROPERTIES:
:
:DATE: <2020-12-05 Sat>
** Presenter
Edwin A. Salsitz MD
Mount Sinai Beth Israel
** slides                                                            :ATTACH:
:PROPERTIES:
:DIR:      /Users/nick/org/data/
:END:

** notes
- getting accreditation - apparently only after everything has been completed, done at www.cmeuniversity.com, course is 14834
- I liked the way he related addiction to food, specifically as a way to help non-addicts understand what is going on in the sometimes incomprehenisble brains of addicts.
- Slightly hilariously pointing out that "heroin" is a Bayer brand name and he shouldn't be using it in a CME class.  Used to be able to get free samples, lots of Heroin side products - lozenges, cough drops.  Mrs Winslow's Soothing Syrup.
- Firmly believes that opiate addicts should stay on opiate agonist therapy for life
- critique of methadone clinics and that form of treatment - separating and isolating addicts (and their treatment team), making it harder (at times impossible) to prescribe outpatient MAT.  Also methadone clinics very rare in rural areas!  Until buprenorphine.  Now, more patients treated with buprenorphine than methadone.  Started in 2000.
- Fentanyl driving opiate overdose deaths - once fentanyl added to urine toxicologies, most people admitting heroin use have fentanyl in their urine, usually not even knowing this.
- Effective opiate treatment is *maintenance*. Opiates are safe over the long-term, used properly.
- Physical dependence *does not equal* addiction
- No pharmacological treatment for alcohol, cocaine, or tobacco is as effective as buprenorphine / methadone.  No real analogous product.
- No question that opioid agonist therapy is the treatment of choice for pregnant women.  Breastfeeding recommended in this situation.  Smoking tobacco (by mother) makes neonatal withdrawal worse.
- *syndemics* - his word of choice - psychosocial background and determinants of addiction.  Says from Lancet.
- Impaired alcohol metabolism after gastric bypass surgery leading to AUD!  By year 2, 10% have AUD (with no history of use).  No association with other drugs, just alcohol due to impaired metabolism.  Roux-en-Y (RYGB) only.



literature mentioned:

Kakko, J., Svanborg, K. D., Kreek, M. J., & Heilig, M. (2003). 1-year retention and social function after buprenorphine-assisted relapse prevention treatment for heroin dependence in Sweden: A randomised, placebo-controlled trial. Lancet (London, England), 361(9358), 662–668. https://doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(03)12600-1

Morgan, D., Grant, K. A., Gage, H. D., Mach, R. H., Kaplan, J. R., Prioleau, O., Nader, S. H., Buchheimer, N., Ehrenkaufer, R. L., & Nader, M. A. (2002). Social dominance in monkeys: Dopamine D2 receptors and cocaine self-administration. Nature Neuroscience, 5(2), 169–174. https://doi.org/10.1038/nn798

Woodard, G. A., Downey, J., Hernandez-Boussard, T., & Morton, J. M. (2011). Impaired Alcohol Metabolism after Gastric Bypass Surgery: A Case-Crossover Trial. Journal of the American College of Surgeons, 212(2), 209–214. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jamcollsurg.2010.09.020

