* CP/AACP Psychiatry Update - Henry Nasrallah - Psychosis and Neuroinflammation
:PROPERTIES:
:DATE: <2020-12-09 Wed>
:END:
** Presenter
Henry Nasrallah MD
** Slides                                                            :ATTACH:
:PROPERTIES:
:ID:       D04387FE-5DDC-4E30-883C-BF5C90FA8453
:END:
** Notes
- Association of schizophrenia throughout the entire course of life, practically from conception.  Numerous maternal infections can play a role.
- Association of autoimmune diseases
- Estrogen can mitigate microglial transmission, this can be the reason for higher incidence in females over 50
- All kinds of things can lead to microglial activation - stress, malnutrition, maternal infection, head trauma, as well as infections obviously
- schizophrenia associated with microglial activation
- higher density of microglia in schizophenic brains
- Heavy marijuana use can lead to microglial activation
- Consequences of microglial activation:
  - Activation of apoptosis
  - Proinflammatory cytokines
  - Oxidative stress
  - Nitrous oxide production
  - NO + TNF-alpha
- 2nd gen antipsychotics can be neuroprotective
- As can all kinds of antiinflammatory medications:
  - Omega-3 fatty acids
  - minocycline
  - ASA, COX-2 inhibitors, NSAIDS
- Neuroinflammation might lead to myelin degeneration
  - Interleukin-1-beta increased in CSF of first episode schizophrenia
- Elevated inflammation associated with a low treatment response
- Most indications seem to indicate that use of all these anti-inflammatory agents most effective /early/ in the course, or to prevent conversion from prodrome to psychosis
- Neuroinflammation may be the /earliest/ sign of schizophrenia, depression and bipolar disorder

** literature mentioned:

Hu, X., Zhou, H., Zhang, D., Yang, S., Qian, L., Wu, H.-M., Chen, P.-S., Wilson, B., Gao, H.-M., Lu, R., & Hong, J.-S. (2012). Clozapine protects dopaminergic neurons from inflammation-induced damage by inhibiting microglial overactivation. Journal of Neuroimmune Pharmacology: The Official Journal of the Society on NeuroImmune Pharmacology, 7(1), 187–201. https://doi.org/10.1007/s11481-011-9309-0

Laskaris, L. E., Di Biase, M. A., Everall, I., Chana, G., Christopoulos, A., Skafidas, E., Cropley, V. L., & Pantelis, C. (2016). Microglial activation and progressive brain changes in schizophrenia. British Journal of Pharmacology, 173(4), 666–680. https://doi.org/10.1111/bph.13364

