* CP/AACP Psychiatry Update - Marlene Freeman - Postpartum Mood and Anxiety Disorders
:PROPERTIES:
:DATE: <2020-12-09 Wed>
:END:
** slides                                                            :ATTACH:
:PROPERTIES:
:ID:       45ECDEA3-15FB-47E5-BDD4-8767F10570E7
:END:
** notes
- Postpartum depression most often had an initial presentation of anxiety
- Postpartum OCD vs postpartum psychosis
  - OCD - ego-dystonic thoughts, avoidant behaviors, low risk of harm to baby
  - psychosis - not ditressed by thoughts, ego-syntonic, often do not show avoidant behaviors, higher risk of harm to baby
- Breastfeeding - association between anxiety and depression and breastfeeding, particularly failure to do so
  - "People feel like they can say whatever they want to visibly pregnant women"
  - And with breastfeeding, increased sleep disruption
  - If a woman is exclusively breastfeeding she will get very little sleep
  - "We don't need women to form a relationship with the pump."
  - Making it OK to supplement with formula.  Bonding is the most important thing.
- Postpartum depression risk factors
  - no one hormone implicated
  - thyroid dysfuntion is common (hypo- or hyper-)
  - Behavioral sensitivity to gonadal steroids has been shown, but currently no way to test for this - only apparent sfter the fact
- Predictors of postpartum depression
  - Hx of depression
  - Stressful life events
  - Fam hx of postpartum depression
- Risk for postpartum psychiatric illness - history is the major one.  Depression or psychosis 50-70% recurrence
- Screening / detection
  - Edinburgh Postnatal Depression Scale - 10 item scale
- Does screening translate into treatment?
  - that part is more challenging!
  - Several studies show that screening in obstetric setting has not (yet) yielded higher rates of treatment engagement
- Treatment:
  - Gold standard: psychotherapy + medication.  Lowest effective dose of medication
  - Care with medication + breastfeeding, but don't want to undertreat!
  - SSRIs and breastfeeding well-studied, low levels of drug in breast milk and infant serum
  - Sertraline has consistent reports of low levels of exposure, but that doesn;t mean it is the only choice.  History of good repsonse most important
  - Little data for newer antidepressants, and MAOIs
  - Brexanalone
    - Tx requires hospital stay of 4 days
    - IV analogue of allopregnanolone
    - Rapid onset of benefitrecurrence
    - Not clear when covered by insurance
  - Best evidence for prevention is psychotherapy
    - Not as much evidence for antidepressants as prophylactic for PPD, even in women with history and high risk of PPD.
    - But sure worth talking about restarting a medication postpartum
- Postpartum psychosis
  - 1-2 per 1000 pregnancies
  - Rapid, dramatic onset within 1-2 weeks
  - Majority have bipolar or schizoaffective d/o
  - i.e. more likely to have a history of an affective d/o
  - Estimates: 4% of women with postpartum psychosis commit infanticide (though infanticide likely under-reported
- Tx of postpartum psychosis
  - Virtually always requiring inpatient hospitalization
  - r/o medical conditions
  - Most will need to stop breastfeeding; could be offered breast pumps?
  - Good response to lithium (Bergink et al 2015 is good meta-analysis)
- Prevention of postpartum psychosis and bipolar d/o
  - difficult!
  - May be possible to defer tx until immediately postpartum
  - But bipolar d/o in particular has high rates of relapse without medication during pregnancy
- Prescribe *sleep* during pre- and postpartum
  - esp in bipolar d/o, sleep deprivation has as high a risk of induction to mania as antidepressants do
  - Also prescribe *support*
    - groups - one is Postpartum Support International
- Mood stabilizers and breastfeeding
  - lithium is a tricky one - worst toxicity is with breastfeeding.
  - But since lithium can be so effective, best course may be to suggest stopping breastfeeding
  - /Could/ carefully follow both mother's and baby's Li levels - but this is controversial (and Dr Freeman suggests discouraging this)
- Avoiding interactions between OCPs and psychiatric medications
- Paternal or partner depression in 10% of cases

** literature mentioned:

Bergink, V., Burgerhout, K. M., Koorengevel, K. M., Kamperman, A. M., Hoogendijk, W. J., Lambregtse-van den Berg, M. P., & Kushner, S. A. (2015). Treatment of Psychosis and Mania in the Postpartum Period. American Journal of Psychiatry, 172(2), 115–123. https://doi.org/10.1176/appi.ajp.2014.13121652

